data.review: You just need to be consistent with your readings. Interest should not be a problem, if you read and are in sync with the material, the prompts and quizzes won't be daunting at all. Loved this course with all my heart, cried during the last class.
Not the best classes but very easy and only a few assignments, so it's easier to work for a grade
Prof Majundar is so incredibly sweet, and all his readings are especially engaging. As long as you do the readings for each week the course shouldn't be too challenging.

It's entirely asynchronous so didn't enjoy that much, please the DSes were far more useful than the lectures. But, no attendance and grading is relative based on three quizzes so if it works for you, it works for you
TAKE THIS COURSE
Nothing to worry about, the best experience ever
The second half of the course dropped in quality bigtime but nonetheless if I do end up doing a minor/concentration in philosophy, it's going to be because of Snyder he's a great guy

The coursematerial is interesting however it's all over the place. There is no fixed structure and we didn't know about the grading scheme till the last week, they are using relative grading. The tf's are not lenient, no matter how much they believe they are.
If you're taking 5 courses in a semester and PoS by Pal is one of them, you're taking 4 courses in that semester. The obvious con is that you don't get to learn jack but, oh well.
Attend your class and switch on your video. Don’t miss prompts unless absolutely necessary. Participate in DS
If you’re not a science kid, don’t take it.

This course is like a revision for people who had maths till 12th it's not very easy but ya is very doable and the course load is very less . Other than a paper on every Wednesday ( in groups of 5 ) there is no other assessment.  And no attendance policy is there . Best 11 out of 13 assessments ( the one which take place on Wednesdays)  are considered.
Great course, no workload, no readings.
This is a must take course. Gkg is the best. Everyone should experience this.
Only difficult thing is the final paper. It’s 3500 words and very confusing. But otherwise it’s an okay course.
Dont take this course if you didnt have science in +2. Professor id very passionate about what he teaches but can be very fast while explaining the concepts.
Its one of the easiest QRMT FCs you can take without having to put in a lot of effort. Non-math people, this is your lifeline
Best for people who are into western philosophy and are not interested in eastern philosophy at all. Well structured course.

Fairly organised course in the beginning but shit hit the fan in the end. Also, the lectures were asynchronous (literally youtube links) so although that makes handling the attendance part of it a lot easier because all you have to do is attend the DS once a week, it’s slightly annoying because it basically becomes readings and DSes, i don’t think i’ve spoken to prof like more than once the entire semester. the grading is SHIT, so so terrible so if you want all As, don’t take this course. abhiraj was a good TF (apart from his grading which made me want to murder that man in his sleep) but the other two TFs people have had several issues with so keep that in mind. So, the content of the course is good and if you have a good TF you’ll be fine but i, personally, would not recommend this course to people because it’s been the most frustrating thing to deal with this sem.

It's a really great course. The course load is heavy, you will have to do your readings because you have to write a comment about it and there is quiz at the beginning of each class. But the readings are great, and even though the comments seem like a lot of work you'll get used it and be a better writer for them. You'll have to write a mid-term essay, but they give you the prompt well in advance. Saying this makes me question my entire existence but I actually enjoyed writing the essay. The end sem is creative group project, which is also fun if you're doing it with people you like. You won't get great grades if you don't actually work of them, but the TFs give meaningful feedback so you can actually improve. The attendance policy is strict, they tell you at the very beginning that you can miss only so many classes and so many prompts, and then cut some of your grade for absences beyond that. But the prof is great and the lectures are so much fun. I'm planning on doing a Lit minor just because I enjoyed this course so much.

This course is just... really boring. Maybe it's just my dislike for math but it's literally like being in professor Binns' history of magic class in Harry Potter- no one is awake and the professor is a ghost droning on for an hourand a half. The TFs are nice and they're trying their best, but nothing can save this course tbh. My TF was Saurabh and his connection issues are so severe that 70% of the DS is spent waiting for him to join back. There's quite a few quizzes, and they get harder as the sem progresses. I'm pretty sure there is an attendance policy but no one follows it. So just do yourself a favor- if math isn't your favorite subject,  you are not gonna sail through this course.
Super interesting readings if you think you'll enjoy philosophy and stuff but hard to score. TFs graded very differently. Watch recorded lectures at 1.5x, Prof is a slow talker.

Good course, if you’re genuinely into history you’ll enjoy it but prof’s style of teaching is kinda boring, i would zone out everytime and towards the end of the semester, i stopped listening entirely. there’s just a mid sem assignment and an end sem assignment so workload is honestly not that bad. i used to skip the readings a lot of the times but it doesn’t really matter unless you care about your participation grade too much. chill course, not too stressy, as long as you do a good presentation and write a banger essay, you’ll get through easily.
Basically just 11th-12th grade chemistry taught again in 6 months. Don't take if you didn't have Chem in school, but if you did you're basically guaranteed an A.

The course is amazing, it will most definitely change your perspective on literature (especially if you're coming from CBSE like me) NGL doing the close reading that prof expects of us can be a little tough in beginning or even till the end but it will certainly expand your horizons

It\'s so much work!! But if you\'re interested in philosophy the material is great. The prof took asynchronous classes and held a discussion hour once a week. You have to put 7 "thoughtful" comments on every reading (which are sometimes very long and very dense) but after a while it becomes fun because you start discussions on the text with the people in your ds. You\'ll have to write 4 four- sentence papers, 1 250-word paper and 2 500-word papers. The four sentence papers will haunt you. Now I had heard that the course was very well organised online, but for us the 250 and 500-word papers were a bit of a mess. They sent out prompts for the 250-word paper very late, had to cancel a 500-word paper and readjust the grade breakdown, and postpone the final paper submission by a week. I\'d say if you\'re interested in philosophy it\'s a great course, but if you\'re not willing to put in the work, don\'t take it.

Tough course with lots of coursework but if you like Math you'll probably enjoy it. Everything was take home so you can use the internet to score well and towards the end extra credit balances out the tough assignments at the start. Still, lots of work and will eat away 3/4 weekends because of assignments.

The course is extremely interesting, and it really prepares you for the semesters ahead. The course load is pretty heavy, and Sitapati grades on a curve, which is why you'll have to work hard all throughout if you want to maintain a good average. However, atleast for me, the course was very rewarding. The material is very engaging, the classes are always fun, and you get a pretty good grasp of society and economics. If you want to do a Poli Sci or an Econ major, would 10/10 recommend this course. But do take into account the extremely hectic workload, it can be overwhelming at times.
Amazing course, has quite a few readings but they are pretty fun reads. Grading is pretty easy as long as you’re consistent in attending class. The tfs are really helpful too.

It's asynchronous, so it's not as if we can engage with the professor. Although that should change when we go offline, so it shouldn't be a problem. It's very well structured and planned in advance, overall great course.

This will be be very different from the EVS you did in school and it will certainly not be a walk in the park, having said that the prof will give you some of the most thought provoking readings and challenge many of your pre conceived notions about the world.

Garbage course, will make you hate Math and consider doing an English major. It's not even that it's too hard or that it's a lot of work, it's just SO BORING and I cannot see the point of one thing we're learning.

The professor has cancelled class 5 times last minute, and we haven't had make-up classes for 4 of them. He doesnt send a OH schedule, and even if we mail him for OH there have been instances he has cancelled those last minute too. Other ICT courses seem so much interesting compared to this class. He doesnt have an attendance policy so theres barely any class discussion since students dont attend. (i attended all classes so i can attest to this)

The only thing you have to submit are weekly group assignments. There are no exams and no individual assignments. So, you'll have to do about 2 questions a week for this course and that is all. The lectures though are extremely boring. I can't say much about the TF though, I don't think anyone ever made it to the DSs after the first week. If you're worried you've taken on too much with your other courses and need an easy going course to balance it out, this is the course for you.

Fun Math course, nothing too high level but also nothing we've studied in school. If you're good at Math you'll probably do well. There are periodic assignments (6 I think) and tiny surprise quizzes but nothing thats not manageable. DS was basically just for doubt solving didn't attend after the first 2.

best course, jgh is a star (sometimes controversial but a star nevertheless) and our TFs were incredible. the attendance policy is crappy ngl and there is a video-on policy as well. the readings they’re kinda strict about because of the google classroom work, a quiz every morning and you’ll be out of the loop the entire lecture if you haven’t done the reading so in that sense the workload gets a bit much sometimes. but it’s a very engaging, fun, well planned course and might even genuinely make you like shakespeare,, i’m planning on doing an english major because of this course
If you manage to do the readings, the actual syllabus isn't too boring. I cannot think of one thing I've learned from the professor, but the DS was quite fun and the material isn't too bad.
This is much more engaging than other ICT courses, you'll end up talking a lot about feminism and see how to write a good paper. And honestly she was the coolest prof I had this sem
Easily the sweetest professor with the most engaging, participative class. You can literally do whatever you want.

It's an asynchronous course. Prof uploads videos and readings on platforms called Canvas and Persuall. It's a pretty demanding course, especially if you're not a first year- weekly annotations on readings, weekly quiz (very short), 4 reading responses and 2 essays. The grading is a bit brutal if your TF is Akshay. Attendance policy is none, prof holds optional office hours during LS time. But the course is honestly really interesting, i've never been into philosophy before but this course really had me questioning life and all that.

Amaan is the best he’s so chill and literally the coolest person that calling him professor just feels weird. he’s like an extremely knowledgeable, highly educated friend you can talk to about some of the most profound shit as well as about test cricket and b99. the course was a little disorganised though and so far we haven’t got a single grade for anything, the end sem assignment will be the first and last, so cant say much about his grading. but if you get ict w him you won’t regret it AT ALL he’s incredible. 12/10

It might be because this was the first time he was taking an FC but the course was a mess. They didn't have a syllabus at all till about half way through the course and then too it was very vague. I had no idea what was going on. Now I didn't science in my senior classes and that may be part of the reason but an FC is supposed to be for everyone. I think the people who did study science in 11th and 12th found it repetitive because essentially that's what they cover. We were graded based on assignments, quizzes and a final exam. We were given a week to do each assignment and the TFs discussed the answers during that time. The prof though was super sweet and very accommodating.

I'm person who doesn't like like math AT ALL and honestly this course sucked the life out of me. The first half of the course especially focuses on all the mathematical concepts (sets, relations, functions, permutation and combination, probability). If you're like me then this course will you give flashbacks of the horrible math classes you had in school. The only reason I got through this course was because my TF was amazing and she explained stuff in a much less boring way than the prof

It's a very light courseload, no reading outside of class since all the books are covered in class itself, fairly easy grading, tfs are okay-good, attendance policy is strict; you need to have your camera on, two assignments only that count for your grade, prof has a conventional teaching lecture style however the course content is very interesting
TAKE THIS COURSE PLEASE ITS THE BEST. ITS BALANCED. COURSE LOAD HARDLY ANY BUT YOU HAVE TO ATTEND THE CLASSES FOR ATTENDANCE. JUST TAKE IT. ITS THE BEST.

The prof is life changing! She is so cognisant of our needs and problems and is very accommodative. The course content is feminist literature so it was very engaging for me. You get to decide the grading rubric as a class, she just provides the headings she wants to evaluate us on. It does get stressful towards the end in terms of writing your own research paper from the start however, it is very rewarding. Prof is INCREDIBLE and Prerna is an AMAZING peer tutor.

1. COURSE LOAD: A QUIZ EVERY CLASS, AN ASSIGNMENT EVERY WEEK, MIDTERM EXAM, FINAL EXAM 
2. THE TYPE OF ASSIGNMENTS: SO RANDOM. MAKE NO SENSE. SUBJECTIVE ASSIGNMENTS ESSAY BASED DOESNT FEEL LIKE A SCIENCE COURSE 
3. GRADING: VERY TOUGH 
you can take it if you’ve done science. That might make it better. Out of 150 students, about 5-6 survived.
Life changing course. Recommended for first years.

I only gave this an overall 3 because the TFs and the DSes saved me. The prof is not good. He skips from idea to idea in the same sentence. Take another EPS. Not this one. Didn’t listen to one LS and sailed through because the TF was amazing and I was active in all of my DSes. But not understanding anything in the LS is not fun. Don’t take it.

Awesome course. One of the courses that actually helped build an intuition and changed my life for the good. 
Highly, highly Recommended.

Not engaging, not helpful.
Don't take it if you want to learn something. 
May reduce your overall workload for the semester.
Not good.

Prof can be problematic and dismissive to say the least, but course material very interesting, course very well structured, engaging class and very insightful. Grading really depends on your TF though.

Prof is very boring, course also poorly structured. Assignments are tough and grading is group based which can be good or bad depending on your members. No attendance policy lol. Overall id say if u can figure your group and assignments its a very light weight course
really fun, heavy courseload, she cold calls during class but it’s definitely going to change your view on sexuality and the world (also she hates men and marriage)

Won't recommend at all. TFs are very late with grades, but they give grades with a somewhat loose hand.  Honestly, I didn't even attend the last few lectures because they were so boring. Positives: no attendance policy, students not penalized for absence. Also course is more or less light.
The grading is really hard and the TFs don’t adhere to timelines so it’s even harder but it’s really interesting for what it’s worth.

Professor didnt know what FCs meant until someone told him on the first day of class. Assignments are longer and harder than my exs dick. However very objective assignments so make of that what you want to. Would recommend to people who dont rlly care about science.

It's important to be weary of what other work you have, because while you can do well in this course without paying too much attention, you will miss out on a lot of what makes this course so good if you have a lot of other work.
It’s relatively easy if you pay attention in class especially because there are no exams- only 1 group assignment every week!
It’s not too bad just really boring and the examinations are a bit tough.

Very boring course with trash assignments and also one useless olympiad that they will hype too much b4 telling u “psych bitch it didnt really matter u have been pranked 😀😀😀😀” Final assignment is a group presentation and u will be grilled worse than the chicken @ bbq nation.

Exams are going to be tough, with no time for a lot of questions, and Debayan fully expects you to not complete all questions, the course will enable you to think like a Programmer & not be intimidated by code, Take Debayan, and you'll love it, unless for the grade
Bad course. Extremely science intensive. Not recommended for beginners. Heavy load.
Good course by one of the best Profs for history, may tend to get a tad bit boring, DSes with Mercy are wonderful and a good way to cover up if you've missed lectures, other TFs are not very engaging

The course tends to get monotonous at a point, good readings, great TFs, usually easy to get a good grade if you put in some work into assignments, deadlines are at 3:29 am, take the course early to be done with the mandatory requirement of EVS, much lighter courseload than other iterations of EVS

Completely Asynchronous course, good for students who are willing to get a taste of game theory without mathematics, watching lecture videos becomes very boring, DSes are the only way you can stay connected with the course, no assignments for Fall 2021, only Quizzes, can perform good in quizzes only if you thoroughly understand all concepts & practical applications
It was my 17th preference ( yes ashoka hates me) and should have been the 27th
just work on the assignment and you’ll be fine. the prof is a sweetheart but gives killer assignments. chill grading too. fun, but not for everyone.

Don't take this unless you're willing to do 10(!) 20-mark assignments and 3 100-mark midterms/final papers. On the bright side, it helps you better understand the material.
Shitload of work, helpful if you want to learn by doing stuff, but an annoyance if schedule is already heavy. Will not recommend to 1st years unless they plan on doing a Maths major.

Great course, lots of reading. Second half of sem gets heavy. Grading is good-ish. Participation in class matters. But material very interesting!  Prof is interactive and fun (literally cracks so many jokes in class). Also there's a group contest that takes place over the three months.
It's not easy per say. You need to work but it's not impossible to do well.
Take everything the professor says with a grain of salt. In other words, carefully think about what he says. Same for the DS.

No. Just NO. Do not take this class online. Offline, I'm sure the class is amazing. Online? I'm watching ASMR Ashoka. The good prof's fast-paced, softly spoken words blur into a sleep inducing cocktail and the sudden shift in topics serves as little more than clouds on top of brain fog. The material is not uninteresting, but the delivery and the variety of topics killed the course for me. I got perhaps a bit more out of this course than I did out of 2 years of CBSE science, but then again, that's not saying much.

The course is useful, but very philosophical. Avoid if you want to learn more about the standard history of India, not about the development of religion, the vedas, buddhism and the likes. Smashing course, very well delivered by the prof, with interactive break-out room sessions often being held during class hours.

Rudy is really good, hell hole your attention for the entire class, especially if like history. But if your camera is on and you're not paying attention he WILL call you out.
Gopal Gandhi has a very conversational teaching style, is hard to focus personally. He doesn't really have a camera policy.
Lectures are recorded, two assignments per week but the grading for that is automated. Grading for essays is by the TFs so depends on your luck really.

Really good course. Readings were very engaging but also quite heavy, need to dedicate at least 2.5 hrs per reading. Professor is a good explainer and has grassroots experience of what she is teaching. Grading is not easy but not bad either. Only wish the classes were not immediately after lunch coz sometimes focus would falter due to sleepiness...
Kranti's great but the readings are mostly lengthy and boring. TFs take over a month to return papers. Grading is terribly strict.
Yeah, the coursework shouldn't be too heavy, considering the fact that now it's all online and loads of work can reduce the motivation and interest.

Professor Menon is strict and makes sure people participate in class. The texts for the course are very very interesting, but occasionally long and mildly confusing too. Prof makes it quite clear in class that she wants us to get out of our comfort zone. She will praise you if you show her that you've intellectually engaged with the text but can't stand vague, general comments. Every class begins with a 3-4 question quiz, which contributes to overall grade for the course. Camera on policy.

The course load is manageable- surprise quiz every other week and 7 practice sets in total plus final exam. Attendance is not strict, DS is not graded and is optional. The major problem is that this course is not inclusive of people who didn't have math in high school. I absolutely hated it.

One of my favourite courses. If you like pol and econ, you will enjoy the course content. Prof explains readings very well. Grading is moderately strict and on a curve. Course work is heavy but will help you in the long run- weekly response papers, mid-term exam and end term research paper.

Good course if you’re interested in Shakespeare( not the way you read it in school), kinda heavy readings plus they’re a little boring, the prompts are very restrictive, grading isn’t too tough, I decided to not do an English major after this course

Amazing for people who are genuinely interested in math and not just taking it for the sake of getting it over with. The topics are fun if you pay attention but kinda confusing if you zone out. We're put into breakout rooms pretty often to discuss questions- I personally didn't like that because if nobody in your group had paid attention in class there would be absolute silence and nobody would know anything. We wouldn't always discuss the same questions in class, so if you didn't know, you didn't know. Fairly frequent quizzes and assignments. DSs dont happen at all. TFs are not super helpful but grade decently.
The best course, heavy readings, pretty decent grading, a lot to learn, it’s a revolutionary course
A mediocre course, take it if you’re interested in philosophy, the readings are A LOT, grading isn’t easy, teaches you how to argue very well
Not accommodating for neurodiverse students, TFs were bad, prof wasn't reachable outside the classroom
I didn’t like the course much, it seemed interesting in the beginning but there was a huge gap in what the Professor expected and what she taught, grading was super tough

This course can get boring very quickly. Though the professor is extremely helpful, sweet and understanding, however, the content and the lecture style lacks engagement and can put you off to sleep. Assignments are mostly just long answer questions with a 3500 word final term paper on a very vague topic. We did have 1 group presentation that increased interaction between peers.

Professor Rashmi expects you to put quite a bit of time in for assignments, etc. and her weekly readings aren't easy to complete if you have other elective FCs that give a lot of reading assignments too. But she's lenient and understands personal limitations. Gives very good feedback on drafts. Her teaching style is fun and engaging.
The readings are intense, as is the case for all Lit&theworld courses, so keep that in mind.

Though the course is quite hectic with reagrds to reading and writing prompts, Lit and the World by Prof Harris is arguably the best FC out there. The prof is very friendly and you would instantly fall in love the way he teaches.

The course is very simple. No complicated concepts and fairly simple sums. The testing is too easy. Just a weekly assignment that the professor discusses question by question in class before we have to solve them. There's no final exam. And grading is relatively easy. TF is very helpful and the DS makes the course a little more challenging and thought provoking

See, Indian Civilization with Rudrangshu Mukherjee is a history course. If you liked history in school, you would find it interesting. If not, then it may be big boring to sit through 1 1/2 hrs. Still, he is the senior most history prof in the university and actually teaches quite well. He is very particular on keeping your camera on. The TFs are quite poor, though. But the course workload is light. I would highly recommend it.

Honestly, Mind and behaviour with Kranti is one of the hardest course that I had. The readings were too hectic. The TF i got (Medha) is nice but very stingy on giving grades and gives feedback after like 1 month. The prof, though, is amazing. He is super jovial. As jovial as Harris. He explains the concepts very well and is friendly in OH. Though the readings are hard and the grades you get are not great, you really learn a lot. Coming from a CBSE school, I learnt so much philosophy in the 1st sem and that was a wonderful experience, knowing that you learnt sth completely new.

This was supposed to be a foundation course. I am genuinely terrified of maths and don't see a point in doing it again in college however out of all QRMT options this seemed the best because it was different and I have no background in computers but I always interested in knowing more. The professor is amazing and the course is different and nice. However the way it is structured is unnecessarily heave and demoralizing for people like who dont understand shit no matter how hard you try and that's okay too. You get some and you dont get the rest. But for an FC it is way too demanding and time consuming and pointlessly complicated. I love rewatching the lectures and revisiting them to understand concepts better but how do you expect me to draw connections in a short span of time when you conveniently forget I have other courses too?I genuinely loved the theory content for this course but I ended up burnt out, low on self confidence, miserable and exhausted by the end of it. My other FCs suffered. No matter how much effort I put to work for this course it seems to go wasted. It got mentally draining in a bad way. Can you please focus on remembering someone of us don't know shit about computers and your firehose method just might result in me drowning under so much of it. Like the professor said, when you look back at the day you started and where you are now I've come a long way and it is amazing but I would never recommend this to anyone ever for the sheer reason that when you make it so drilling and intense it sucks the fun out of it and missed the whole point. This isn't about the grade drop also, its about the journey which you wish just came to an end by the end of it. The prof also said he doesnt believe in the concept of exams and exams are 50 percent of our grade. I got to learn so much but when people who know CS can just figure things out that you just cant and then everyone has moved to the next topic it gets weird. Chill out on the course structure. Give more psets I have learnt more by sitting with my peers and working on understanding and doing the psets than anything else. Puzzle day was crazy but still rewarding. It's a good course but I dont see a point to it till you restructure the way it should be conducted.. Before taking this course everyone told me Debayan is worth it. I'd agree Debayan is amazing but not the FC. I will definitely keep up with all the new concepts I learnt theory wise and will take up python in the future too all because of Debayan but honestly not for a good long time and the way this FC is structured is to blame. Also for apple's sake please make fixed DS. All the TFs are amazing but they have such distinct ways of teaching you end up way more confused than sorted by the end of it. I am sorry for this long rant but I have cried way too much in this course to not say this out loud. I will gladly work through pain and Debayan makes me want to but it's just too much and not worth it. Limit topics and tests please. And remember some of us just suck at math in general an answer involving trigo in its explanation that too applied is killing. And trust me I gave this course everything I got and the reason I got worked up is because despite all of it I just couldn't perform in exams. Just couldnt get the questions  lastly I'll just like to say the first class with Debayan assured me this was one of my best decisions by far and by the last class it was all toppled over. I can assure you there are many like me whether they say it here or not who feel the same. We want to love this experience like all the others in this course but please give me a chance to be able to do that because right now it's just not doing it for me. I am dumb when it comes to QRMT and I am self aware enough to know that  I am ready to push myself for it too but if you are forcing me to do it then please don't make it more difficult than my 12 years of school math trauma and more. I have nothing against anyone honestly this is just my POV and I was extremely miserable so I wanted to put it out there . I didnt take an easy collaborative math course because this was different. Dont make others afraid to do this like I am now because of such experiences.
Prof Alok is so so so nice even if I have something to say in criticism to this course I will not because Prof Alok is so nice.

Great course. The grading is super easy, both the major exams are open book, and you have a week to submit them. This is a very interesting course, and the classroom discussions are always superb. Course load is okayish, pretty doable. You'll be able to breeze through. Eric is a really good teacher as well.

It would have helped if you got grades at least once but this class was undoubtedly the only reason I remained sane this semester. I am genuinely sad this ended it was life changing and prof Kundan makes you feel like you belong here one some of the lowest days that you are having. Everything about this course is so perfect I am so so glad I got him this sem. And the things I learnt here and way more than just thinking and writing and my 18years of life combined.

Literature and the World with Professor Burgers is great course; you should keep up with your readings, they're long but Prof makes the classes super fun, very engaging and hilarious dude; workload is a little on the higher side but it's definitely a course worth taking.
requires constant work. tfs are great. grading is fair. not lenient but fair. makes you a more aware reader.

Prof Brara's EPS course is pretty bland during the lectures; however, the readings are pretty fun, a little obscure and difficult but the TFs help; Discussion Sections are the most fun and they account for quite a bit of your grade. The lectures aren't recorded though and attendance weightage is a little strict. Overall 5/10.

Bro don't take this course. Just seriously, don't do the Calculus Enabler with this guy. Professor himself is a lovely person and very sweet but the course is work heavy, assignments every week, and it's relatively graded. On top of that, it's not easy at all and it takes up a lot of your time; my mental health took a big hit because of this course and I performed poorly sometimes in other courses because of how time-consuming the work was.

Professor Shreyas is a man of acute intellect and he loves the sound of his own voice. That said, the man is brilliant, he's going to give you advice and teach you things that you can actually apply in academic writing and he's very engaging. Classes with him are intimidating because he will force to reevaluate your own thought process quite a lot, but otherwise helpful and humorous and very chill.

lenient attendance policy. weekly assignments and a quiz every class. a little all over the place. the tfs’ gradings are rather confusing. prof is nice. but i don’t feel like i got much out of this course.

lot of readings. prof is very well knowledgeable in her field her lectures are interesting. tfs take ds participation quite seriously (they note down names and stuff). you can skip on readings tho because there is no immediate check on it other than ds participation. grading is fine. somewhat lenient.

strict camera-on policy and it’s an 8:30am class. profs lectures are like a story. interesting, but can put you to sleep. prof is a super no nonsense type of person. grading is pretty lenient. no regular assignments other than the mid term and final essays. no readings. great course. would recommend.

it's a really good course but the classes were asynchronous. It didn't bother me too much but some people might not like it. Though the professor takes group office hours during the official class time.
Perfect course for first sem, its easy and engaging
This is a difficult course for the first sem, especially if ur a slow reader
this is a great course, strict attendance policy, and to do good in it, you have to be present in it, like actually present. keep an open mind, and just listen to everyone

this course is a highly TF dependent course mainly because when I was studying it the professor just gave recorded lectures so there was no lecture attendance, and there one optional discussion hour per week, which was not graded. So, the interaction with the professor was minimal. The grades depend on your TF, and one of the TFs was a highly absent one and would take ages to give grades, however, one other was great, and the third one gave strict grades, but was overall nice. However, this course is an engaging one, and you'll love it, if you're willing to put in effort. There are bi-weekly readings which are usually long, on which we have to leave comments which are graded by a system, and there are papers we have to write. In my case, the professor completely went MIA, because he was sick, and wasn't responding to anybody's emails, so one of our papers was cancelled, and a lot of confusion was caused due to that. But, overall, i still love this course, maybe it's just because my Tf is lenient, but its a good course.

this is one of the lightest courses I have taken, and the only reason I don't love it is because I don't like science as such. Otherwise, its an easygoing course, no such attendance policy, in the lectures or DSs, not many assignments either, and good TFs.

This course is great, its an interesting one. A drawback is that the professor seems to be a little confused, and the syllabus is very tentative so you might not cover everything listed in syllabus doc at all. Moreover, he does not use slides in the lectures, and we only have to listen to him, which is fine , except he uses the phrase 'you know' a lot. Otherwise, the Tfs are great and there's not a lot of workload.
The course is extremely unorganised and TFS seem incompetent, please do not take this course please.

Not an entirely bad course in the sense that you can maneuver your way through it. However, if you want to save yourself some brain cells and not spend three months dissecting Shakespeare - don't take this course.
Amazing course even if you're not too interested in EVS. Very manageable workload, stimulating discussions and helpful TFs. Overall an organised course that encourages critical thinking.
No attendance policy is a green flag. It's a very manageable course, especially if you're from a non-science background and want to get PoS over with.
Logistics wise extremely disorganised but content wise very interesting. Grading is very good but only take this if you are low-key interested in Indian History.

Prof's really cool, course material is very engaging though the first half was a little more theoretical than I expected. very unstructured though, lot of non-CS kids were understandably lost. Workload is mildly heavy, psets are cool but exams are brutal and puzzle day is wildly frustrating. Grading is great and very fair, if a little inconsistent cause it's a huge course spread across a lot of TAs. TAs and office hours are lifesavers
Wish I'd put down joost or gil for my first pref though

Great light course, no attendance policy which is great because the profs and lectures are ridiculously boring. Not a lot of work except for exams which need studying. Relative grading + extra credit is nice, TFs are very nice but grading is inconsistent between them I think

It was on game theory so very interesting material. course is completely async and has no workload, which sounds great but for me personally it was a disaster because I paid no attention to anything, learnt nothing and didn't do well either. Grading is across three exams, no participation or assignments necessary, but for monsoon 2021 the exams fluctuated wildly in difficulty level. DSes are much more helpful than the lectures, I should've attended them

The course overall was okay. Very light work and super easy to get through. A big problem many of us had was with the TF, Saurabh Vatsa. I feel like he didn’t really care about being a TF. He shows up late, and a couple of times not at all, and rarely responds to emails. It was quite frustrating. The course also felt disorganised sometimes. It’s like the TFs didn’t even communicate with each other. Each one has different ideas of what citation styles to use and even what the word limit is.

Such a great course. Joost is hilarious and a really accommodating professor. The TFs were lovely. I don’t love literature but this course made me start reading again so that was nice. Also I really liked the readings. Highly recommend

It’s a pretty good course. The prof, the TF (Tarun) and the TA (Sid) are really nice and very approachable. They’re very communicative. The one problem is that grading is extremely slow. It’s December and we still haven’t gotten our grades for the midterm paper yet. The course is also not the most organised, which stressed me out a little, but it wasn’t too bad. They’re just very laid back and flexible on dates (not due dates though. Get your stuff in on time). Other than that, its a nice course with engaging lectures. There’s a decent amount of work but it’s light, so very manageable.

This was such an amazing course. My TF, Sanjana was really sweet and the DSes were nice. I’ve heard the other TF, Sanjana is a bit intimidating and not too friendly or open to hearing people out, though. There’s quite a bit of work. Morning of the lecture by 10am you have to submit a 100 word comment on the reading for that day. Grading is fair and the feedback is really helpful. Highly recommend

It was the first time the professor took an FC, and well he shouldn’t do it next sem/year. I want to major in political science but his course was so soul-numbing I am questioning my interest in the subject:/
The course doesn't require too much work, except during the midsem and end sem exams. Includes a group presentation and a book review as the only other workload.
Heavy on class participation and group work. Lot of readings are assigned, but not too particular on the follow up

Attendance policy is not strict. Coursework is also not that heavy. Only mid terms and finals, no extra assignments. The classes can get a little boring but some of the texts assigned are really interesting!!

If you don't have a passion for learning history, this course will be really boring. A ton of readings are assigned, no real consequences for not following through but it does it make it tougher to follow.

Prof. Roy is the most beautiful being on this earth. I definitely recommend this course. The readings are great and the classes are engaging. Deadlines don't matter all that much, she just wants you to understand the material.

Very disorganised course, students had to tell him we need a plan. Generally felt like the professor was kind of winging it. But it's a pretty basic course if you have a science background. Pretty lenient marking too.
*This was my 27th preference*. Good course if you're from science background. Not engaging though. Guidelines and structure isn't set.

Interesting course content, slightly unstructured and lectures may get monotonous at times, grading is great, light courseload (only mid-sem and end-sem assignments), DSes are engaging but depends on the TF as well. The profs are great but sometimes it's difficult to take notes in Prof Gandhi's lectures because it's more of a conversation than a lecture. Recommended readings are lengthy but quite engaging.
Really engaging material but can be long sometimes.

If you are fine with spending most of your weekend working on a maths problem maybe this is the best course, it's a challenge almost every weekend and you learn a lot, if you are willing to work for it you will love the Prof and SPIVAK. Not an easy course so no heavy workload and grading till now has been brutal.  Prof tells quite a few jokes and is accommodating with deadlines... so you can cry on your assignments for a little longer if you want.. but at the end it feels worth the pain

Its basically high school chemistry + history about some prominent names, if you want a recap of that go for it, you can literally search up most of the answers from google. The Prof is really knowledgeable so its a pity that this course offers nothing more to what I have learnt. Its an easy grade but I feel like i should have taken some other course.
Dude..  its debayan... the class, material and Prof are super fun. Best course ever, you have puzzle day, and you get the grade you deserve with extra credit assignments and also ask for vivas.

Best class, I realised how narrow minded I was, learnt a lot the reading get a bit boring at times bit class discussions are the best. The movie recommendations are really great.. you get ti bind with a lot of your course mates because of the small class size, so one of the most memorable courses.

Snyder seems nice but he's incapable of leading an engaging class. the course material is actually pretty good but he finds a way to make it boring. assignments are never uploaded on time, and then he'll make some sorry excuse in class and say they'll be up in the next day or so then fucking forget again. I'm still waiting for the final paper to be uploaded rn while typing this, no idea when he's gonna get around to making it and it was supposed to be out last week. he didn't even grade our midterm papers yet it's fucking ridiculous. weekly quizzes are always late. honestly this is the only class in my life where I've actually fallen asleep. i had taken this fc on the advice of a cohort leader but I'll ask you to do yourself a favour and take MnB with literally anyone else.

I mean it's evs. Don't expect much. prof seems genial enough but lectures will still put you to sleep. an empty piece of paper is more engaging and charismatic and accessible than the teaching fellows

The professor and TF are amazing it’s the course material itself that makes the course less than stellar. But for those who absolutely dread math and want to get over with the FC, this is the right course. The math  is relatively simple and you are graded solely on weekly assignments that you do with a group. No exams!

Pretty average course but that’s because of the TF I had.Saurabh was unhelpful did not answer to emails and conducted DSes in the driest fashion possible. But professor Lahiri is very knowledgeable and engaging which makes the lecture sections interesting. There aren’t too many readings and only 2 assignments. It’s an easy course if you are consistent and pay attention.

Great course, feels a bit unstructured at times, but great prof and really interesting material. Really really challenging 2 exams, but you apparently get a good grade even if you understand the absolute basics and put in the work. 

Grading system: 
We had 2 stressful exams with a lot of weightage (20% each I think) a midterm and a final, 1.5 hours ish each, too many problems and very very less time, although debayan mentions that he doesn't expect us to do all questions on the exam. 
Rest of the psets (3 psets and 1 extra credit pset for the rest of the grade) were fine, some problems were tough and I'm still not sure I understand the solutions, but we're given plenty of time and extra credit questions. 
Puzzle Day accounts for like 15% of the grade. Really challenging (and sometimes frustrating) and takes up the entire duration (we had 48 hours). You need a good team for puzzle day. Can get stressful if you have other exams due on the same weekend. But overall great experience and the hints session that debayan holds makes it all worth it.

This is not a math intensive (or math-y in the slightest sense) at all. 

Would 100/10 tell you this is not a course to miss.
Good professor, fun and interactive classes - almost everyone participates, grading is mostly good if you put in the effort - lowest seems like a B-

Challenging course, tough grading on assignments but overall grade will be good if you actually put in effort into all your assignments, attend classes and discussion sessions. Classes were asynchronous and there was trouble with the assignment deadlines in finals week. One of the tf's returned graded assignments very late but other than that 10/10 recommend the course.
Just really really really boring.

Grading system is horrible because its based on 3 MCQ type quizzes over the course. No attendance policy, no marks for anything but the quiz and no extra credit work. It is relative grading however so the grades get somewhat normalized. That said, course material is very interesting and the TF is the absolute best.

Great course, profs are both amazing but their teaching styles are very very different and the transition was a little more sudden than I hoped for. Prof Rudy is a little stricter and has a traditional lecture style but Prof Gandhi is very interactive and a little abstract. The grading is very fair and the Tfs this year (Heeral) was amazing. 10/10 recommend
Too much work. Sai (my TF) is hardly available. Hardly get responses when we mail the TFs.
If you were a science student in 11th and 12th then take it. It is almost a repeat of class 11 and 12 chemistry.

Decent course, recommended for those without much science background (but much easier with), definitely check if better PoS courses are available, pros: it's good if you wanna get this FC over with, Professor Alok is really sweet and has helpful slides; cons: not-so engaging material with random project work and somewhat interesting discussions rarely, and the exams can be stressful, probably won't change the way you think
Very easy workload, interesting content as well. One TA sucks, rest I loved this course.

Very interesting course material but Professor (tho really sweet and nice) was a mess, classes cancelled, not rescheduled, finished half of what we planned to do, if you're a fast reader and study on your own in your own pace>great; if you depend on structures for learning and procrastinate, or slow reader>might be a bit harder to keep up

Great course, but what you take from it=the effort you put in, pre-recorded lectures and you can still get the work done somewhat without watching all of them (it's definitely recommended tho); experience is really different based on TF, one of the TFs half the course to return the grades and the other TF was really sweet and nice in DSes but their grading would make you sad for a week (but had constructive criticism that actually helped to improve)

I think the course was very inconsistent and dissociated in the way it turned our as compared to course content mentioned on AMS. Even the assignment timeline and gradings were highly irregular. We used to watch Hank Green crash course videos instead of proper lectures and very few people in class had the motivation to interact, but everything was extremely tangential than being well put up.

The course is Biology and Philosophy oriented. L. S. Shashidhara is pretty damn monotonous - he teaches the bio part (which is quite repetitive if you have him for another course - I did). Dhruv Raina is still better - he teaches Philosophy related stuff. Overall the course is boring but the workload is not at all heavy. You have 2 exams during the entire course and one book presentation + book review. The TFs are the nicest and most helpful people. They'll clear all your doubts, they're also pretty accomodating with the deadlines and all too. And they're reachable too. Can't say much about the grading since we haven't really gotten our grades back - I don't think they're meant to be disclosed (?). All in all its not a course that'll change your life but it's fine if you just wanna get it over with.

I don't think I need to say anything about Debayan Gupta - he's the chillest and the coolest Professor that there is. Very very accommodating to everything. My TA for the course was pretty good - answered all my doubts, very sweet and helpful and reachable. However some TAs didn't reply to emails for days. The TAs also take forever to grade assignments. The workload is a little on the higher side but manageable. You get 4-6 problem sets on average throughout the course + mid sem and end sem exam + puzzle day. The course structure is very very interesting and engaging, everybody loves it. The only thing that made me regret taking this course was the exams. They're like 200 marks papers for 90 mins - pretty damn tough and it's very easy to flunk them. But Debayan gives many extra credit stuff to help you get a better grade. Also, it might be quite complex and intimidating for non CS students but if I managed (PCB Student), you will too. Overall, I'd totally recommend this course, it's been one of a kind experience.

The course was overall good. Professor Lahiri is the sweetest person. The TFs are alright - mine was good but Saurabh I've heard is very incompetent. He didn't turn up during specially scheduled meetings, rescheduled so many DSes etc etc. The course material is alright, you get readings every week but it's manageable to navigate without them - I did. The Discussion Sessions are very important - don't miss them. They carry 25% of the overall weightage. The course load is THE LIGHTEST I've ever seen. Only 2 essay submissions, one mid sem and one end sem that is literally it. So you only need to know stuff and readings relevant to your essay topics and nothing else. I liked the course all in all and would recommend taking it.

The professors are quite boring, Shashidhara in particular. Prof Alok makes these ppts which are very helpful. The course load is pretty chill - 2 exmas (mid and end sem) and 2 assignments only during the entire course. I found the assignments very very interesting and they were actually pretty damn relevant and not some random stuff that we won't ever use at all. The TFs are also pretty nice and helpful. They'll clear all your doubts and be up for meetings and all. The grading is relative and not strict - it's fair. So professor and course content wise it's a boring course but assignments, workload and TF wise it's a chill course. The course is unlikely to change your life but it'll get you over with the FC.
The prof is good and the papers are not very difficult to write, but this was way too much reading for the summer sem. Might be too much for a regular sem too
Interesting course. The papers do take a lot of work, but the content was definitely what I wanted from a philosophy course
Professor Saran is a great instructor and anyone who is even remotely interested in math will like this course
The professor is nice, but the course can be quite boring
The professor is extremely boring and, at times, barely coherent. The course material isn't very interesting either, but at least the grading is generous
Professor is a bit repetitive and the pace of the course is a little slow, but the content is very interesting and workload is basically just studying for the 3 exams

The course load is not a lot, it is just regular. We are expected to read around 15 pages before each class and attempt a quiz on it with 4 MCQs and 1 short answer approx. Prof is really sweet and accommodating but he is mostly late in posting assignments. Although he extends the deadline when that happens, but it messed with the schedule then. Tarun and Sid are also very helpful. Overall it is a good course.

The first half of this course was with Rudy which was great. His lectures are very structured and he teaches in a story like manner which is very engaging. Although he can be savage at times and is also strict about attendance and mobile phones, he is a good professor. The second half was with Prof Gandhi which was okay. He is really sweet but his teaching style is quite abstract which is not something I personally prefer. The workload is pretty low as it's only mid sem and end sem essays. Although the readings might get a bit too much depending upon your TF. I had Heeral and she is an excellent TF except that she asks to read a bit too much.

His course content is okay and a bit easy to understand even for people who do not come from a science background but the topics are very random. No course structure or outline is provided to us and we have no idea what to expect. There was no link between the topics and prof moved from one to another randomly. Also, some assignments had questions where we had to write letters which was quite subjective and pointless. Otherwise, the course is okay and Gaurang is an excellent TF. The course load is neither too much nor too little.

Prof is very nice and chill. Svasti was our peer tutor and she was great too. It's just that I felt that Prof does not push those who speak less in class and she is a little biased towards the girls. Also, she kind of assumes that everyone knows about feminism but that might not be the case.

Absolute trash prof, no clue what he's doing, workload is insane (an assignment every week plus two drafts of a thousand word op-ed plus two drafts of a two thousand word research paper plus a twenty minute presentation plus having to put up with this idiot's ramblings every week), grading is non-existent, hasn't returned a single grade all semester so you never know where you stand. Course material is decent but not more than any ICT course. If you get any choice at all pick amaan or arpita or literally anyone except this clown
the readings and course structure is amazing plus very very fun no forced interaction/participation but still engaging. super funny prof

my favourite course of the semester. she was from a pol sc/IR background and am actually contemplating changing my major to pol sc fr. checking is kind of strict not in the grading sense but she reads and gives feedback for every single sentence and so overall this course was v helpful too
if you care about grades take it !
The best course with the best professor. The grading is very fair and the course content is deeply interesting.
The course is alright but the professor was weird and the TA was rude.
Easy A honestly. Profs are v v smart if you go and ask them questions. But it's also very monotonous :"
Very informative course. Prof is nice and accommodating and just generally very very nice. Would recommend 10/10

Literally the best course on the PLANET if you don't take this you're fr fr missing out. She is always open to the dumbest questions on earth and doesn't mind if you say you don't know the answer. She will try to understand where you're facing a problem and work with you till the end. Literally you should never miss a class because it's just that good. Even if you don't practice too much on your own, just sit in the classes and you're good to go ^-^ she's perfect and ilh

just too good. Rudy online wasn't the most fun experience because he imposes his views on you and doesn't tell alternative theories when they very clearly exist so meh. But GKG is one of the smolest sweetest best prof ever who will validate you till the ends of earth even though whatever came out of your mouth was trash.
stay on top of the course always because the deadlines will come crashing on you and leave you a beautiful train wreck
Taka Prof Saha's course if you genuinely like math and believe that you actually want to learn, because the difficulty of this course will not make it easy for your sem.

The course is pretty fun and engaging. The lectures were amazing and I always looked forward to attending class, however, the grading is pretty tough (also, questions in assignments and exams are tricky and subjective, so, it is not very easy to score good marks). Also, no attendance policy for lectures, however, there is one for the DS.

It's Pant. Great guy, interesting prof, course is quite engaging. Hard grader. You gotta be a pro at econ or dont expect a very good grade. Does not have a lecture attendance policy but attendance is counted using DS attendance. Has two quizzes in a sem that are quite hard. Class participation counts in the form of Google Classroom questions that you have to answer. Strict grading again. Its a nice course, quite informative and prof is also super cool but the grading is quite hard.

100/100. I highly recommend Krittika's course. Extremely helpful and also super engaging. The coolest prof ever. Courseload varies from week to week but usually is not bad. Krittika is very accommodating, extremely helpful, very very well-versed with her area of expertise. Her classes are great fun. Fair grading--not extremely lenient but not tough either. Id say the grading is quite proportionate to the amount of effort you put in. Highly recommend her course.

Decent course. The readings are decently challenging and you are required to annotate them every week which then accounts for 20% of your grade. Its quite doable though. I barely ever spoke in the DS which also held decent weightage but the TF still gave me a good score. Not a super easy course but isnt the most challenging either. Grading is quite good.
easy A as long as you submit
My TF was Anirudh Raghavan. Dude is a gem. Best tf. Just make sure you go for office hours before writing the paper, and STRICTLY stick to what he says if you want a good grade.
Grading was unnecessarily difficult, even though the TFs (especially Tamanna) were sweet and accommodating. Course fucked up my sem 2 grades. Missed an A- by one point.
The most boring material, she teaches like a CBSE science teacher from 3rd grade, and she is not open to newer point of views. Anyone who diverges from her thought process loses marks.

Just don't. I was expecting an A. Like legit no joke A because I thought I did amazing on my final paper. I had 88% before final paper grading and was expecting it to bump up to 90 to get an A. Then the pathetic TF destroyed my grading and I got not A-, not B+, but rather a B (75-80%). Single letter drop!!! And the best part? You see there are two TFs and I had asked a few questions to my TF which they agreed was okay to write in a paper. Then surprisingly the second TF grade mine for IDK what reason and cut marks on those same points and that the other TF agreed was okay. I could not appeal either. I really hope the TF gets kicked out of Ashoka. Ruined my GPA for no reason. Absolute dogshit piece of garbage TF. The people from this class reading this know who I'm talking about. Be warned future class takers. Can't believe Ashoka is wasting it's resources hiring bullshit fuckin assholes like them.
Hit or miss for so many people, but literally life-changing if sheâ€™s a hit for you.

This is an unbelievably rigorous course. The work load will be a lot. There will be a quiz every week. There will be 2 mid-term exams and a final exam. These exams will take a lot of time as they will be take home. The grading was not as tough as what was mentioned in the course information handout, but it was difficult as compared to other courses. The learning curve will be very steep. If you already have a lot on your plate, I suggest that you should not opt in for this course. The advantage of taking this course is that you get a chance to build a great personal rapport with the Professor and make some really good friends because of the really small class size. The course encourages collaborations and discussions. Professor would be happy to give you a lot of extensions. It is up to you to decide on how you plan to manage the work load. Keep all of these factors in mind as you take a decision with regards to this course.

Snyder is absolutely wonderful, but the course might be a bit harder than expected for some people (and way easier than expected for others), so go through the syllabus/readings once before registering.

Kaustav is a good prof. However sometimes the class can become to discussive that it can be boring. He sometimes rushes the topic when he doesn't have time and thatts not good. But overall, it was a course that i would not rate as 'bad'
Arpita is a nice prof and the course is interesting. Sometimes, she may not agree with your viewpoint however convincing it is,but other than that, itbwas a good courses
One of the best courses at Ashoka. Srinath Raghavan is an amazing prof and i would recommend him anyday

Math for Econ is a tough course no matter what prof yiungey die to the jump from school to college level math. But Prof Arora is not and and though the grading is hard, i would not mind taking her again

First of all, this course was not offered by Professor Rajendra Bhatia. It was offered by Professor Sourav Ghosh. The OAA has incorrectly mentioned Professor Bhatia as offering this course on the AMS. I would strongly recommend that you take this course offered by Professor Sourav Ghosh. There will be 4 assignments plus a bonus assignment. You are allowed to discuss these assignments with anybody, including the TFs. WARNING: DISCUSSION IS ALLOWED, COPYING SOMEBODY ELSE'S ANSWERS IS NOT ALLOWED. The course had take home exams. A very important thing to keep in mind is that if you do not understand something, please interrupt and tell the Professor that you do not understand it. Do not hesitate. Keeping quiet would be a big mistake. It is perfectly okay to not even attend a single lecture for this course. All lectures are recorded, and there are no restrictions on access to the lecture recordings. However, my suggestion would be to not bunk lectures and be regular. This will help you. Also, all assignments and exams have bonus questions. Do not leave questions, even if you are confident of getting 100 percent. You must attempt all of them. This course is to be enjoyed.
The course is easy but Komal is a very poor prof. I got away as it was an intro course, otherwise it would have been hard.

I would suggest that it is best if you do your homework seriously, be punctual, attend all lectures, and solve ALL the questions given by the Professor. This will guarantee that you will have a nice time.

I do not feel that this course has been rigorous. Attendance has got marks. Most of the times, the pace of the course was too slow. There is a strong possibility that you might get bored. A lot of important topics were barely given adequate emphasis. The grading is easy, but my suggestion would be to not opt in for this course since you would barely be learning anything substantial and this might be a loss for you as you go ahead and pursue advanced courses.
Readings were boring sometimes but Professor explained the entire thing in class which helped . Only 2 assignments which made the course load easy but heavy weekly readings.
Really abstract which makes material difficult to understand. No proper course structure which was very irritating

The first half of the course was taught by Professor Rudrangshu Mukherjee. All the lectures were a monologue with only the Professor speaking. Whether you find this to be interesting or not will depend upon whether the topics interest you or not. It could go both ways. The second half was taken by Professor Gopalkrishna Gandhi. His lectures were very interactive and it was fun to be present in class. You will need to write one assignment each for the first half and second half of the course. WARNING: DO NOT PLAGIARISE. DO NOT MISS LECTURES AND DISCUSSION SESSIONS. Take the course policy seriously.
SHITTIEST COURSE EVER!!!!!!!!!!
You need to score above 66% to pass this course, according to the guidelines ;)

No attendance policy. Prof uploaded videos on Youtube which was really helpful. Very nice and answers every question. Only assignments were 7 homework. TF was also very nice and responsive. Probably the best course I took this semester. If you actually study for this course then it is an easy A.
Professor only takes early morning classes (8:30am-10:00am) and is extremely strict about the attendance. Offline exams where u need to write 3 essays in 90 mins..

Prof did not teach the last topic just because of low attendance. Nobody understood what is the basis for grading. Very strict level grading. TF is also not very brilliant as sometimes he taught us wrong things, when verified from the book. I don't even know how he became a TF?
Prof has attendance policy. If you have a science background then this course is a must take and a piece of cake for you.
Prof uploaded videos, but I don't know if this will continue. Fair/Strict grading. If you want to have a wholesome taste of philosophy and psychology then this course is highly recommended.
One of the coolest Ashoka profs to exist! Classes are super engaging, grading is fair - if adequate effort is put in, you will end up with a good enough grade.
This course is not for the faint of heart, 'cause a lot of your beliefs are going to be challenged here. Strict attendance policy.

The material is interesting, and prof provides well maintained notes. However, the grading policy of the course is extremely unfair. It negates the effort put in by the student throughout the semester and instead only focuses on comparing the entire classes grade with a single student.
its enriching but so hard! Prof is really strict with grading.

The course wasnâ€™t structured very well and the professor wasnâ€™t very engaging. Course material seems interesting, but the classes actually drained any and all enthusiasm I had towards wanting to learn.
A very boring class with a pretty strict attendance and grading policy. It was online and I could barely stay awake when it used to go on.
Interesting course material, and the professor is very sweet and helpful.
Quite an easy course imo with no attendance policy and the gading was pretty fair as well.

loved the course, heavy courseload and grading is tough as well, large amounts of effort in essays need to put for an A. Liked the course so much would want to take more bazaz courses in the future because of it.
this course is pretty easy to get an A in, however the professor and the content taught is great. Would highly reccoment
Very tough grading, but great course for prospective English majors. Convinced me to do an English major by the end of it.
Biased. Be very careful.
The grading is insane for an FC. The material is interesting enough but the class is pretty boring.
Easy course if you put in the work. He reduced the grade boundaries, which really helped alot.
Amit Goyal is bad

It's the most time pass CS course you can find. Lectures are disorganized, topics jump from one to the other, no structure to the readings (we'd just get 15-20 links of articles to read in every online lecture, and then when we shifted offline the readings just completely stopped). Very easy to get a good grade, barely put in any work and didn't even follow most of what was going on in class but still got an A. I guess the course can be good if you like Debayan's style and put a lot of extra effort on your own.

The course content is just fantastic. The Sipser book that we followed is really good and almost everything I learned was through that only. The Professor is very weird, passive aggressive, and often quite mean to the students. Teaching wise, he seemed a bit unprepared and seemed to skip over important stuff just because he didn't feel like teaching it. Further, the assignments are very uninspiring as he just asks textbook questions and everyone finds the solutions to those on the Internet anyway. The course content is so good that it's such a pity that such a course was ruined due to the incompetence of the Professor.

Professor Jhawar is by far the best CS Prof at Ashoka. The first half of the course where we covered perfect secrecy, pseudorandom functions, pseudorandom generators was brilliant. Jhawar's enthusiasm for the course content, motivation of the problem statement, and rigorous treatment of the subject matter would induce goosebumps in me. The second half of the course fell off a little bit as the assignments were not nearly as challenging or thought through and the final exam was way too easy and didn't result in a satisfying culmination of the course.

Lectures might be a bit difficult to follow but the course content was amazing. I got to know so much more about the environment and that too in a real world context. At school, EVS used to be just a bunch of boring definitions. This course changed my old mindset and made me more interested in learning about our environment and the groups that are affected by it.

This course will require a lot of work. I remember once we had our class exam till 9.40 pm and a class test in our LS the next day. If you want to take this course, take it for the professor. She lays more emphasis on learning rather than getting good grades. This mentality will make things easier to navigate. Professor is always ready and eager to help.
Professor Shreyas in many ways changed my life. He made even the most technical readings fun. This was my favourite course at Ashoka so far.
Hands down, the best course and the best professor ever
Teaches well but can't pace the course. Insists on absolute grading and no concessions until the end. Paper exams with no reference or internet.
Extremely low-effort, almost everyone got an A. Cheating rampant on exams and easy weekly assignments. You'll learn a lot more with the other profs though
Very easy, low effort course. No attendance policy and all assignments were take-home (atleast for this sem). All solutions are googleable and grading is absolute.

A little too math-heavy, doesn't get to any of the interesting bits until the last couple weeks. TFs are not very good, grading isn't on time and inconsistent. Prof isn't big on giving students As. Teaching works though, and lays the mathematical (but not programming) foundation for CS.
Very boring, low effort for work but need to attend at 8.30 w/ cameras on if its online. Fairly easy to get an A if you pay attention in DSes/use notes but also easy to slip to a B if you don't
The easiest class I have ever attended not excluding kindergarten. Dependable way to get a calc requirement out of the way, all while actually teaching material in case you'd care to learn.
Moderately easy A or A-, but the 'great books' in question were all mid.
I somehow know less after this course.
Bodhi is a lenient marker while Hansika is a strict marker, so there was a huge descrency in the grading

i had a brilliant time with the course, professor is extremely approachable and open minded. i was able to connect with her both inside and outside class hours and it was absolutely beautiful. much of what I was exposed to in this course has been beneficial for me as i can apply this knowledge beyond the classroom walls. definitely recommend this course to aspiring literature and history major/minors.

Prof tries his best to give everyone a good grade (A, A-), the course content is relatively easy but makes sure you thoroughly understand the foundations of calculus. It's profs first time teaching calc so I'm assuming he will increase the course difficulty/ cover more advanced topics as he gets the hang of what students need. Very very sweet prof, food teacher, just teaches a bit slowly.
Literally my favourite course from this semester, Prof is so wacky and cool, he will blow your mind.
Absolute disaster. The professor's diffidence while taking classes was super evident. Cheating mostly went unchecked. But god what a waste of a course slot

He looks like the nicest, most engaging teacher at first (which is why i was misled into taking his course even though multiple seniors warned us), but his grading is ass, to put it in a nice way. The gap between teaching and questioning is too wide so I did struggle with his course.
10/10 recommended even if you dont want to pursue socio. only 2 assigbments over the whole sem no participation grade and no attendance but the kost amazing classes and readings ever

I learned nothing at all. Introduction courses should ensure a good base for upcoming and more technical courses but this course was not. My class 11-12 eco knowledge was the only thing i applied in this course. I wish i hadnt taken it.
The most boring professor ever. Take any course except this. She takes abrupt pauses in the middle of the lecture and the awkward silence is just unbearable.

Coursework deals with a lot of philosophical abstract ideas but extremely rewarding if youre interesting imo, its one of the courses that definitely helped me grow as a person and the professor is v sweet and down to earth.
The TF was the best thing about the course but otherwise made interesting material kinda boring but the feedback the TF gives is very very helpful.

Not a great course for people who have any experience with creative writing at all. It feels redundant and repetitive, and the course structure is too loose. Prof is a lovely person, but can sometimes say the same things over and over again, and there wasn't really much space for class discussion. We didn't have too many assignments, the assignments piled up at the last minute. Not hard to get an A, but hard to really engage with.
Lovely prof, nice readings, very engaging and interactive classes. Kundan is chiller than you think.

This is a must-take Deepak Mehta course- prof is genuinely vvv nice. He's damn funny and sarcastic, so lectures were very engaging and fun. That being said, getting an A in this course is a bit difficult. Most of the time, we'd get 50 page readings the day before the lecture so we wouldn't be able to read them properly in time. The readings were very interesting, but they were also very difficult to get through and understand. If Anirudh is your TF, he'll explain every reading beautifully in his DSes, but he is a vvv strict marker and his feedback can be harsh. On the other hand, Titiksha didn't show up for DSes sometimes and had no idea what was happening in class.
do yourself a favor and donâ€™t take this course. material is okay but prof is not

kinda boring and prof only just reads out of the slides, barely any interaction so it might get monotonous or just painful for you if you're not interested in the subject but it's bearable if you are. hardly any workload since the readings are often skippable and there's only a mid-term and an end-term.

prof was amazing as always but the course was a lot heavier than i expected. we also seemed to keep circling back to the same topics and conversations and i think there wasn't enough space to truly analyse the readings the way we wanted to, it felt like there wasn't enough freedom on that front so it was just a little frustrating. made me lose most of my interest in pursuing english, tbh.

originally pretty well structured course but prof didn't quite do justice to it. the lectures were hard to follow, worksheets weren't spaced out properly so most of the workload fell on the last few weeks of the sem which was hard to cope with, they weren't graded on time either. prof was nice and understanding, gave extensions easily and was all in all very approachable and kind but isn't really a great teacher.

Good course, heavy courseload but the readings were interesting. A lot of the readings were very relevant to current affairs. Be warned- there is a written exam for the final. It accounts for 30-35% of your grade and gave me board exam flashbacks.
Prof is great and funny. It's more of a conversation rather than a lecture. Very interesting course material and the nicest TF'S ever. Pretty good grading too.

SO MUCH WORK. A LOT OF WORK. Check it out if you aren't sure about your major or minor, otherwise don't. Prof is nice but she isn't accommodating and their grading policies are weird. They don't explicitly mention things and then cut a whole lot of marks. I lost 4 marks due to citations- apparently paraphrasing also requires citations. Not an Easy A, really have to work for it

This is the easiest POS ever. It is literally class 10 science. The professors are actually titans in their fields and overall nice people but not very engaging, but this course is a piece of cake. If you're looking to finish off POS quickly, take this one.

A pretty well structured course, heavy on the academic readings, but class discussions are always fun. Kundan is extremely accommodating regarding attendance issues/deadlines, super friendly, and a great facilitator of discussion. Not the best course for people who require structured deadlines, grading policies, etc. but ideal for people who need flexibility and understanding.

Don't go into this course for the grading. You really have to work very hard to get an A, it is reserved for the most exceptional people. Here are my two cents of advice- take notes, write down what prof is saying, it will really help you with the assignments. DO THE READINGS. Prof is really nice and this course does expand your horizons, attend the classes and you'll know if literature is your thing or not.

anyone who tells you GB with Rudrangshu is an easy grade is a liar. Sure, it ultimately is an easy grade because there are only two assignments in the entire course, but the books were boring after a point and I fell asleep in almost every class. Additionally, PLEASE DO NOT TAKE THIS COURSE IN THE EVENT THAT CLASSES IN MONSOON ARE ONLINE- PROF HAS A MANDATORY CAMERA-ON POLICY.
