IF YOU DO NOT SWITCH YOUR CAMERA ON IN CLASS, YOUR ATTENDANCE WILL NOT BE MARKED. Did I mention this class was an 8:30? oh yeah so CAMERA ON AT 8:30 IN THE MORNING IS TORTURE DO NOT DO IT.

Worst course I have taken at Ashoka. The lectures are boring and conservative, the readings are all dense, too much time is spent on each reading with nothing really being said about any of them. The grading rubric is ridiculously complex. TFs were lovely, though. That's about it.

I was really reluctant to take the course, but it is incredible. There are very few people, and a light work load so you have an opportunity to engage with prof and the class. Most of the grading is done through presentations, and Prof is good with his grading. How much you learn entirely depends upon you and your interest in the course.

Beautifully structured course, can occasionally be heavy in terms of readings, but the lectures are worth it. Getting an A does require a lot of work, and its best to ask the Professor to clarify whether the course will be relatively or absolutely graded at the beginning of the semester.

honestly, Kranti's MnB is a good course because it really helps improve your writing! Your entire grade has several components to it so if you read the course syllabus doc carefully and are smart about the way you work, it's easy to get an A-/A. Overall, it's a must-take Ashoka course. That being said, the readings gave me an existential crisis, 4 sentence papers made me cry, I hate philosophy, and Immanuel Kant is a piece of shit. Sayonara :)
Biased. Be very careful.
You learn math in this course, fr. You get the grade you truly deserve. You HAVE TO put in effort in this course, otherwise, god help you.

Rudy's course get a bit monotonous and boring, Gopalkrishna Gandhi's classes are more engaging. Grading is easy and the attendance policy is a bit stringent. Overall easy course and you will learn new things about Indian History.
You actually learn math in this course.

It was a decent FC. Prof. is knowledgable. TFs were helpful. They basically taught the canon of Pol. Theory in this course which students may not find interesting, but as a course it was pretty decent. Do the needful and you get an A which you'll learn 4 weeks into the course. Not bad.
Loved this course a lot, it is a very discussion based class so if you're into that then it's a win for you. There are reading quizzes before every class but they are damn easy so no need to worry
It's chiller compared to Kranti's course, but DO NOT, and I repeat, DO NOT choose Hansika as your TF. Her grading sucks.
Don't take this course if you want to learn programming.
Absolutely zero work, just attend classes and the final performance and you'll get an A. You don't need to be a dancer to take this course coz it's very basic steps.
Prof is still new at this job so does have a lot of enthusiasm, he's very sweet and understanding but the amount of reading for this course is insane so keep that in mind

Pourvaja is a tough grader but she gives solid feedback. Take this course if you can sit through lectures and are okay with writing nuanced essays for a english litertaure course disguised as an FC. I'd say it's a little bit of work for an FC, but it's more or less fair, so keep it as a 2nd option.
Course load is relatively light, one midterm, one final, one paper and one presentation.

Okay, given that this course got a 3 for every question, I would suggest you take this course if: 1) you're willing to squeeze 14 weeks of work into 7, 2) if you're a CS major who wants slow lectures but content is covered more or less properly.
The prof is amazing, not too many readings, a few short written homeworks sometimes, and two main papers which carry maximum weightage. If you work hard enough, you'll surely get a good grade.

Prof is willing to talk if you approach him, but he wants the course to be tough. So people who have no prior knowledge will not find the course "introductory". Be prepared to die at least once. Also, the course is quite unstructured, I think it was more of an overview of what awaits you in CS@Ashoka rather than a properly structured gateway course.

The prof is really great and she is so damn knowledgeable, you are bound to learn a lot from her and there were only 2 assignments so the workload was also not that bad but the readings can be a little heavy tho. However keep in mind that atleast this time the assignments had absolutely nothing to do with the readings so technically you can ace this even if you have done no readings but honestly they are worth it so go ahead and read them

While I found the courses boring the readings were interesting. Further, we have more leeway to do what we want on the final project, so we can do pretty much anything we want related to the course themes.
Very engaging course, if youre interested in history at all I'd 10/10 recommend it.

we had to do 4 annotations on each text (often more than 2 texts a week) so online this was an easy but SUPER interesting course but on campus, it was HEAVY workload considering you'll be more occupied. AMAZING course though, heavy courseload in terms of strict weekly deadlines and perusall grading rubric is tricky but the lectures are among the best I've had at ashoka and prof. raghavan really gives you a ground up view of a lot of important ideas that you ought to know about as you go through the learning experience at ashoka. genuinely an amazing course and i'd recommend to anyone who can put in minimal consistent effort and wants to have a good experience in a course
Ayush Pant. What more to say.
The chances are if you're taking this course then you're not a science person but honestly this course is easy enough and you can get through it pretty easily

Fantastic course, a lil heavy on the readings but every single one of them is worth it (if you bother to read them), super light course load - only 2 assignments in total and absolutely no grading for attendance, participation etc. Anirudh is an amzing TF, grades VERY fairly; show up and do your work and you get the grade. Fantastic course overall 11/10 would recommend.
If you do well on your final paper you get a good grade. But the course itself is boring
workload is chill, grading is super chill, if you hate science and want to get through pos, take this!

It was an amazing course, prof has this really cute grandpa energy, but my the TF who graded my final paper really tanked my grade and was very mean in the feedback so I'm very salty about that but do take this course
Course was pretty unorganised which was the main problem with it
The course has multiple submissions, however each of these are very easy to complete and help boost your grade. Professor is very experienced but the course is very simple even for an intro course

boring course online and irl but on campus, the tf (gaurang) was way more helpful. course material was WAY too spread out. take this course only if you've got a decent base in math/probability/permutations+combinations and you should get an easy A. I didn't and I got an A-
best course ever <3

this course is SUPER interesting and definitely makes me excited to learn more in the coming semesters. could be challenging for bio minors who wanna get the requirements done with quick because there's a bit of math involved but you should be able to cope if you just take notes in class. definitely a fun experience and I enjoyed it
Grading depends so much on the professorâ€™s specific mood at the time.
